{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496999","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496999"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T09:02:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T09:02:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1455"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1455","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1455"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.28,0.34,0.08,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1455"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105952"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1455","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1455"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1455"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88427"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"451"},{"type":"tags","id":"1115"},{"type":"tags","id":"1367"},{"type":"tags","id":"2128"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"9419"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12916"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7106"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8036"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38767"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38925"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42325"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44513"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44772"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105952","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105952"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old man presents with a painful ulcerated exophytic nodular lesion on his left forearm (Image). It has been progressively increasing in size for the last two years and is painful and does spontaneously bleed. He lives in a remote area of the Northern Territory with few medical resources, works as a farmer and gives no history of trauma. He has a 20-pack-year smoking history and his medical history includes type 2 diabetes and asthma. On examination his blood pressure is 132/84 mmHg, pulse 76/min and temperature 37.2\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC. Apart from the lesion on his arm, the rest of the physical examination is unremarkable. PCR for IS2404 of the biopsy from the lesion is negative.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Buruli ulcer","Pyoderma gangrenosum","Squamous cell carcinoma","Lymphogranuloma venereum","Cutaneous leishmaniasis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESquamous cell carcinoma \u003C/strong\u003Eof the skin can run an indolent course - as shown in this photograph. The patient lived in a remote area, with few medical resources. He has a history of smoking and is a farmer by profession, causing prolonged UV exposure, both being the risk factors. The initial presentation of SCC includes a history of a nonhealing ulcer or abnormal growth in a sun-exposed area. It is common in US, Australia and in countries near the equator.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBuruli ulcer\u003C/strong\u003E also presents with a painless ulcer with undermined edges later in its course, but it initially presents as a papule contrary to the above scenario. The skin may have a reddish-purple color. The affected area may be itchy or tender. It is caused by \u003Cem\u003EMycobacterium ulcerans\u003C/em\u003E. PCR targeting the IS\u003Cem\u003E2404\u003C/em\u003E sequence has been used as a reliable and rapid method for the diagnosis of Buruli ulcer, being negative in this case excludes this diagnosis. Buruli ulcers are found in tropical areas, particularly West Africa and northern Australia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPyoderma gangrenosum \u003C/strong\u003Eis an autoinflammatory disorder, characterized by a full-thickness ulcer with a bluish-purple border. It is predominantly a very painful condition, but occurs in association with other disorders like IBD, RA, Granulomatosis with polyangiitis, Beh\u00e7et disease, Leukemia etc.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELymphogranuloma venereum\u003C/strong\u003E is a sexually transmitted disease involving the genitals caused by chlamydia trachomatis. It typically begins with a painless genital ulcer followed by swelling of the lymph nodes in the groin, which may be tender. Other symptoms of LGV may include anal discharge, rectal pain and swelling, fever and malaise. This is not the case in the above scenario. It is endemic in certain areas of Africa, Southeast Asia, India, the Caribbean, and South America.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECutaneous leishmaniasis \u003C/strong\u003Eis a skin infection caused by parasite that is transmitted by bite of sand fly. After the incubation period an erythematous papule appears, which can evolve into a plaque or ulcer which is usually painless. The patient does not give any history of trauma or any insect bite and the lesion in the picture does not resemble that of leishmaniasis. leishmaniasis is generally restricted to tropical and temperate regions, majority of them occurring in the Americas, the Mediterranean Basin, the Middle East, and Central Asia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Squamous cell carcinoma of skin presents as nonhealing painful ulcers commonly involving the sun-exposed areas.","Chronic, nonhealing, ulcerated lesions in sun-exposed areas in older adults should raise suspicion for squamous cell carcinoma."],"references":["Edge SB, Compton CC. The American Joint Committee on Cancer: the 7th edition of the AJCC cancer staging manual and the future of TNM. Ann Surg Oncol. 2010 Jun;17(6):1471-4. doi: 10.1245/s10434-010-0985-4. PMID: 20180029. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/20180029/","Australasian College of Dermatologists. Squamous cell carcinoma [Internet]. Sydney: Australasian College of Dermatologists; [cited 2025 Jun 15]. Available from: https://www.dermcoll.edu.au/atoz/squamous-cell-carcinoma/","Hadian Y, Howell JY, Ramsey ML, et al. Cutaneous Squamous Cell Carcinoma. [Updated 2024 Jul 2]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK441939/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88427"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1455"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19441"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19441","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19441"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/f7a88853-cf9f-4c00-ba3f-f3f0975fafc5.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/f7a88853-cf9f-4c00-ba3f-f3f0975fafc5.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":411}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88427","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88427"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-15T10:54:36+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-07T14:12:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1455"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105952"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"de